756
00:42:17,493 --> 00:42:18,933
We end up winning the series,

757
00:42:18,994 --> 00:42:22,331
but it was an incredible,
incredible playoff performance.

758
00:42:22,414 --> 00:42:26,043
I've never seen it before
and I had never seen it after.

759
00:42:26,126 --> 00:42:29,463
That wasn't Michael Jordan out there.
That was God disguised as Michael Jordan.

760
00:42:33,217 --> 00:42:35,344
Nobody like him.

761
00:42:35,427 --> 00:42:37,721
Point blank.
I never seen nobody play like he plays,

762
00:42:37,805 --> 00:42:40,849
and, uh, you can include all of 'em.

763
00:42:40,933 --> 00:42:44,937
Jordan is the most talented player
in the NBA...

764
00:42:45,813 --> 00:42:48,190
uh, by far.

765
00:42:48,274 --> 00:42:50,693
Guys like myself and Larry,
who knew the game,

766
00:42:50,776 --> 00:42:53,279
who knew championship basketball,

767
00:42:53,362 --> 00:42:55,990
we knew the guy was coming. Right?

768
00:42:56,073 --> 00:42:59,660
He just needed the right horses
to go along with him.

769
00:43:00,953 --> 00:43:02,997
We realized
that Michael Jordan

770
00:43:03,080 --> 00:43:05,291
was the greatest ball player in the NBA.

771
00:43:05,916 --> 00:43:09,253
So, a year later,
we basically rebuilt the entire team.

772
00:43:09,837 --> 00:43:11,046
Krause went to work.

773
00:43:12,131 --> 00:43:15,551
We added some great people
like Horace Grant and Scottie Pippen.

774
00:43:16,844 --> 00:43:19,054
We changed the makeup of the team.

775
00:43:20,097 --> 00:43:25,728
I will always give Jerry Krause
credit for assembling a roster that fit.

776
00:43:26,937 --> 00:43:29,398
I'm sure one of the hardest trades
he ever had to make

777
00:43:29,481 --> 00:43:32,109
was trading Charles Oakley to New York
for Bill Cartwright.

778
00:43:32,860 --> 00:43:35,946
We needed a big man.
So, Bill was a great fit.

779
00:43:36,864 --> 00:43:38,032
As much as I love Charles,

780
00:43:38,115 --> 00:43:40,743
this fits us better than
what Charles gives us right now.

781
00:43:41,243 --> 00:43:44,121
Michael was very fond of Charles
'cause Charles was his protector.

782
00:43:44,204 --> 00:43:47,082
Mike was always attacking the basket
and he got knocked down a lot,

783
00:43:47,166 --> 00:43:49,209
and Charles was always the guy
to back him up.

784
00:43:49,293 --> 00:43:51,879
<i>Oakley going
right after "Hot Rod" Williams.</i>

785
00:43:52,463 --> 00:43:54,923
When Krause pulled
the trigger on that trade,

786
00:43:55,007 --> 00:43:57,676
that was probably
one of the defining things in his career.

787
00:43:58,135 --> 00:44:00,262
Charles Oakley and I
were good friends.

788
00:44:00,346 --> 00:44:02,139
We'd spent a lot of time together.

789
00:44:02,222 --> 00:44:06,268
But things were in place for us to win,
you know, when he left.

790
00:44:06,769 --> 00:44:09,188
Jerry did a phenomenal job
with the team.

791
00:44:09,855 --> 00:44:12,691
He made great trades,
made great free agent signings.

792
00:44:12,775 --> 00:44:14,234
He deserves a lot of credit.

793
00:44:14,318 --> 00:44:16,403
But he couldn't get out of his own way.

794
00:44:35,005 --> 00:44:38,384
Scottie had problems with Jerry and, um,

795
00:44:39,385 --> 00:44:41,178
it came out on several occasions.

796
00:44:41,679 --> 00:44:45,265
The thing was... And part of,
you know, Scottie's anger,

797
00:44:45,349 --> 00:44:48,185
was they did look
into seriously trading him

798
00:44:48,268 --> 00:44:50,562
after the '96-'97 season.

799
00:44:50,646 --> 00:44:52,231
Anybody can be traded

800
00:44:52,314 --> 00:44:54,525
and part of my responsibility

801
00:44:54,608 --> 00:44:57,861
is to listen to other teams
when they talk to me about our players.

802
00:44:58,654 --> 00:45:00,906
And we think Scottie Pippen is certainly,

803
00:45:00,989 --> 00:45:02,991
one of the top couple of players
in basketball,

804
00:45:03,075 --> 00:45:04,493
and feel very strongly about him.

805
00:45:04,576 --> 00:45:07,287
And I can't tell you
what's gonna happen in the future,

806
00:45:07,371 --> 00:45:08,371
because I don't know.

807
00:45:10,999 --> 00:45:15,045
Krause's point then was,
"Look, we're gonna lose Pippen in a year.

808
00:45:15,129 --> 00:45:17,089
The group doesn't have that much left.

809
00:45:17,840 --> 00:45:19,425
Let's blow it up now."

810
00:45:19,508 --> 00:45:20,968
But ownership said no.

811
00:45:21,510 --> 00:45:24,138
But I killed that
because I decided that

812
00:45:24,221 --> 00:45:26,974
as long as Michael Jordan
was still gonna be here,

813
00:45:27,057 --> 00:45:28,726
we gotta go for the sixth championship.

814
00:45:28,809 --> 00:45:32,187
Jerry, how close did you come
to dealing Scottie Pippen?

815
00:45:32,271 --> 00:45:35,524
Well, we had a number of offers

816
00:45:36,358 --> 00:45:41,655
we thought were good offers for Scottie
and for some of our other players.

817
00:45:41,739 --> 00:45:44,575
I'm never going to stop being aggressive,

818
00:45:44,658 --> 00:45:48,162
and I will never stop trying to do things
to make the team better.

819
00:45:48,579 --> 00:45:50,789
That really is what sort of...

820
00:45:52,458 --> 00:45:55,419
tarnished my relationship with Jerry.

821
00:45:56,336 --> 00:45:59,631
He tried to make me feel so special,

822
00:46:00,632 --> 00:46:06,430
but yet, he was still, like,
willing to trade and do all that stuff,

823
00:46:06,513 --> 00:46:10,100
but never would tell me to my face.

824
00:46:11,560 --> 00:46:13,437
<i>After you're in the game for a while,</i>

825
00:46:13,520 --> 00:46:16,565
<i>you realize that nobody is untradeable,</i>

826
00:46:17,357 --> 00:46:19,943
<i>but I felt insulted.</i>

827
00:46:20,986 --> 00:46:26,658
I sort of took the attitude
of disrespecting him to some degree.

828
00:46:30,370 --> 00:46:32,623
There was always barbs
going back and forth,

829
00:46:32,706 --> 00:46:35,250
but at a certain point,
Scottie crossed a line.

830
00:46:36,585 --> 00:46:39,546
I mean, it was getting... personal.

831
00:46:40,839 --> 00:46:45,511
Pippen started abusing Krause openly,
cursing him out on the bus.

832
00:46:45,594 --> 00:46:49,431
Couldn't tolerate him anymore.
Didn't respect him.

833
00:46:51,183 --> 00:46:54,353
I remember some shots coming
from the back of the bus.

834
00:46:55,813 --> 00:46:57,481
Raise your eyebrows, you know.

835
00:46:59,316 --> 00:47:04,238
Pippen started berating Jerry Krause...

836
00:47:05,572 --> 00:47:06,824
in front of the team.

837
00:47:07,574 --> 00:47:12,746
We had to say, "Hey, let's hold it down."
You know?

838
00:47:12,830 --> 00:47:15,999
But that's when it was, like,
"Hey, there's a divide here."

839
00:47:16,083 --> 00:47:20,462
It's not your normal...
I mean, there's some hard feelings.

840
00:47:20,546 --> 00:47:22,256
"You don't appreciate me.

841
00:47:22,339 --> 00:47:24,508
You're trying to trade me.
You won't pay me.

842
00:47:24,591 --> 00:47:27,761
Well, screw you.
I'm taking care of myself now."

843
00:47:29,054 --> 00:47:33,225
I was at that point where I felt
like I needed to do what was best for me.

844
00:47:34,893 --> 00:47:37,396
I felt like it was time for me
to go shopping.

845
00:47:37,479 --> 00:47:40,190
Pippen is now demanding a trade
and he says

846
00:47:40,274 --> 00:47:43,861
he will not return from the injured list
until he is gone from Chicago.

847
00:47:43,944 --> 00:47:46,363
He said he's never gonna play
for the Bulls ever again.

848
00:47:46,446 --> 00:47:48,448
"I'm never gonna wear this uniform
ever again."

849
00:47:48,532 --> 00:47:51,452
Should the Bulls do something
that would make you want to stay?

850
00:47:52,077 --> 00:47:55,622
I mean, no. I don't...
I don't see myself carrying on.

851
00:47:56,832 --> 00:47:59,626
Scottie made some
earth-shattering comments last night

852
00:47:59,710 --> 00:48:02,588
to one of the Chicago writers,
about wanting to be traded.

853
00:48:02,671 --> 00:48:06,008
- Can we get your thoughts on that?
- I don't really have any right now.

854
00:48:06,592 --> 00:48:09,720
I felt like Scottie was being selfish.

855
00:48:09,803 --> 00:48:12,222
Worrying about himself as opposed to

856
00:48:12,306 --> 00:48:15,851
what his word was to the organization
as well as to the team.

857
00:48:17,895 --> 00:48:20,063
I'm done here,
you know what I'm saying?

858
00:48:21,064 --> 00:48:24,359
You've already written my script out
that this is it.

859
00:48:25,485 --> 00:48:27,988
So, I had to do what was best for me.

